Pareto Plots

Bruce Hartman

Pareto Plots

Pareto plots are a good way to understand what’s important in creating unicorns or increasing their valuation. We use the summarized data frames for Count and TotVal.

Pareto Functions for Plotting

We use the qcc package to create Pareto chart data from the count data. Then we use ggQC package to create Pareto graphs of Total Valuation by year. We define two functions in a separate file.

  • pareto_data_structure creates a Pareto data structure
  • pareto_plot_object creates a Pareto plot object from the structure.
source("paretoplotbuilder.R")

Pareto Plots of Count

for (yr in 2015:2021) {
  uu = pareto_data_structure(y, yr, which="Count") %>% remove_rownames
  uu%>% filter(CumPct<80)
  p=pareto_plot_object(uu, yr, which="Count", main="Pareto Plot")
  print(p)
  # ggsave(paste0("Pareto Plot Count Year ",yr,".jpg"), plot=p, device="jpeg")
}

Pareto Plots of TotVal

Calculate the Pareto plot data and make the plot.

for (yr in 2015:2021) {
  uu = pareto_data_structure(x, yr, which="TotVal") %>% remove_rownames
  uu%>% filter(CumPct<80)
  p=pareto_plot_object(uu, yr, which="TotVal", main="Pareto Plot")
  print(p)
  fs=uu
  print(fs)
  # ggsave(paste0("Pareto Plot TotVal Year ",yr,".jpg"), plot=p, device="jpeg")
}

Save Pareto Plots of TotVal

for (yr in 2015:2021) {
  uu = pareto_data_structure(x, yr, which="TotVal") %>% remove_rownames
  uu%>% filter(CumPct<80)
  p=pareto_plot_object(uu, yr, which="TotVal", main="Pareto Plot")
  print(p)
  # ggsave(paste0("Pareto Plot TotVal Year ",yr,".jpg"), plot=p, device="jpeg")
}

Total Valuation by Class and Year

A barplot will be useful.

pv=ggplot(x %>% filter(between(Year,2016,2021) )) + 
  geom_col(aes(Class, TotVal, fill=Class)) +
  scale_fill_manual(values=c("blue","yellow","red")) +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 0, vjust = 0.5, hjust=1)) +
  labs(title="Total Valuation by Class and Year") +
  facet_wrap(vars(Year), ncol=2)
pv

# ggsave("Valuation by Class and Year.jpg", plot=pv, device="jpeg", height=7 )

Count by Class and Year

A barplot will be useful.

pv=ggplot(y %>% filter(between(Year,2016,2021) )) +

  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 0, vjust = 0.5, hjust=1)) +

Valuations by Year and Country

for (yr in 2016:2021){
  p = ggplot(cbi_more %>% group_by(Country, Class, sum(Valuation)) %>% filter(Year==yr)) + 
    geom_col(aes(Country,sum(Valuation), fill=Class), alpha=.6, position="stack") +
    scale_fill_manual(values=c("blue","yellow","red")) +
    theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, vjust = 0, hjust=.5)) +
    labs(title=paste0("Total Valuation by Country Year ",yr))
  print(p)
  # ggsave(paste0("TotVal by Country Year ",yr,".jpg"), plot=p, device = "jpeg", height=7, width=10)
}

Next we leave out the USA because it is so much bigger in later years.

for (yr in 2016:2021){
  p = ggplot(cbi_more %>% group_by(Country, Class, sum(Valuation)) %>% filter(Year==yr, Country!="United States")) + 
    geom_col(aes(Country,sum(Valuation), fill=Class), alpha=.6, position="stack") +
    scale_fill_manual(values=c("blue","yellow","red")) +
    theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, vjust = 0, hjust=.5)) +
    labs(title=paste0("Total Valuation by Country x-USA Year ",yr))
  print(p)
  # ggsave(paste0("TotVal by Country x-USA, Year ",yr,".jpg"), plot=p, device = "jpeg", height=7, width=10)
}

Investors

v = cbi_more %>% select(Company, Year, Class, Valuation, SelInvestors)
invlist = selinv %>% pull(SelInvestors) %>% str_split(", ")
CompanyInvestors=data.frame()
for (i in 1:nrow(selinv)) {
  c = selinv[i,"Company"]
  y=selinv[i,"Year"]
  cl=selinv[i,"Class"]
  va=selinv[i,"Valuation"]
  invl = invlist[[i]]
  li = length(invl)
  # print(li)
  ytemp=data.frame()
  for (j in 1:li) {
      ytemp = bind_rows(ytemp, data.frame(Company=c, Year=y, Class=cl, Valuation=va, Investor=invlist[[i]][j]))
  }
  CompanyInvestors = bind_rows(CompanyInvestors, ytemp)
}
CompanyInvestors %>% slice_head(n=20)
summary(CompanyInvestors)
CompanyInvestors %>% filter(Year==2021) %>% arrange(Investor)

xyz = function(co, yr, vpi) {
  q =vpi[vpi$Company==co & vpi$Year==yr,"valper"]
  print(q)
}
a=CompanyInvestors$Company[1]
b=CompanyInvestors$Year[1]
xyz(a, b, vpi)

z=c()
for (i in 1:nrow(CompanyInvestors)) {
  a=CompanyInvestors$Company[1]
  b=CompanyInvestors$Year[1]
  z[i]=xyz(a, b, vpi)
  CompanyInvestors$VPI[i]=z
}
